# Project Identity

This repository is for the **SharePoint Travel Planner & Journal** project only.

Do not mix in assumptions, naming, architecture, workflows, components, styles, or 
business rules from:
- LIME
- Coastal Style
- any other repo or project

If something is unclear, prefer the local functional spec and local repository context.

# Primary Objective

Build a SharePoint-hosted travel planning and travel journal application with:
- a private trip workspace
- a restricted shared trip view
- a modern app-like single-page UX inside SharePoint

This project must feel like a real application inside SharePoint, not like classic 
SharePoint list forms.

# Source of Truth

Treat the local functional specification document in this repo as the source of truth.

Before suggesting architecture changes or implementing major features:
1. read the functional spec
2. follow it closely
3. do not silently simplify required behaviour

If a requirement seems expensive or technically awkward, do not remove it silently.
Instead:
- implement the best-fit approach that preserves the requirement, or
- explicitly flag the tradeoff

# Technical Stack Direction

Prefer:
- SPFx
- React
- TypeScript
- SharePoint-backed storage
- SharePoint document libraries for files/photos where appropriate
- modern component-based UI
- inline editing patterns

Avoid:
- classic SharePoint form UX as the default experience
- scattered admin pages for normal editing
- over-reliance on out-of-the-box list pages for core user workflows

# UX Rules

The app must be:
- single-page in feel
- inline editable
- desktop full experience
- tablet full experience
- mobile reduced but still useful

Key UX requirements:
- day selection in left sidebar controls day content in main panel
- itinerary cards expand/edit inline
- selected day shows:
  - day header
  - detailed budget breakdown tile
  - itinerary cards
  - journal content
- timeline treatment beside itinerary cards
- shared view must be clearly distinct from private view

# Private vs Shared View Rules

Private view includes:
- finances
- booking/payment/admin detail
- documents/links management
- reminders/tasks
- full itinerary editing

Shared view includes only:
- simplified itinerary
- journal entries
- journal photos
- likes/comments/share-link

Shared view must exclude:
- financial values
- budgeting detail
- payment detail
- private planning/admin detail
- detailed operational attachment/admin metadata

Do not leak private-only fields into shared rendering.

# Financial Rules

Financial logic is critical.

Follow these rules exactly:
- summary currency display is NZD
- underlying itinerary items may use multiple currencies
- FX conversion uses live daily rates
- use a working amount model, not strict budget-vs-actual variance tracking
- paid items contribute to "Spent So Far"
- unpaid items contribute to "Remaining"
- trip summary cards are:
  - Total Budget
  - Spent So Far
  - Remaining
  - Average Per Day

Do not add a top-level Per Person summary card.

Item-level support is required for:
- primary total amount
- currency
- optional secondary unit type + unit amount
  - per person
  - per night
  - per day

# Multi-Day Cost Allocation Rules

For multi-day items:
- allocate evenly across covered days/nights for day-level rollups
- trip-level totals still count the full value once

Examples:
- hotel -> split across nights
- cruise -> split across cruise days/nights
- multi-day transport -> split across covered days

# Day and Place Rules

Each day must support:
- fixed system day/date identity
- editable display title
- day type
- itinerary entries
- journal entries

Place logic:
- primary overnight place is derived from where the traveller spends that night
- additional visited places may exist for the same day
- editable day title remains independent

Do not create a heavy standalone Places management workflow unless explicitly 
requested later.

# Itinerary Entry Rules

Each itinerary entry must support:
- category
- decision status
- booking requirement
- booking status
- payment status
- notes
- timing/duration
- location detail
- linked docs/links
- related sub-items
- inline editing
- duplicate/delete actions

Required status dimensions:
- decision: Idea / Planned / Confirmed
- booking required: yes/no
- booking status: Not booked / Booked
- payment: Not paid / Part paid / Fully paid

Items requiring booking but not yet booked must be highlightable.

# Journal and Photo Rules

Journal entries:
- belong to one day only
- multiple journal entries per day
- support likes
- support simple comments
- support copy-shareable-link

Photos:
- can be uploaded via journal entries
- can be uploaded directly to trip album
- multiple photos per journal entry
- optional caption per photo
- trip album must support day and location filtering

# Document and Link Rules

Support:
- item-linked documents
- item-linked links
- trip-level Documents view
- trip-level Links view
- search/filter across documents and links

Keep documents/links SharePoint-native where possible.

# Search Rules

Trip-level search must support mixed results across:
- itinerary items
- journal entries
- documents
- links

Filtering by content type must be possible.

# Export Rules

Support:
- Excel export for selected day, line by line
- PDF journal book export

PDF book must support:
- full trip / single day / date range
- cover on/off
- trip summary on/off
- comments include/exclude
- likes include/exclude
- journal include/exclude globally
- individual journal entry include/exclude

# Implementation Rules

When implementing:
- prefer incremental phases
- keep commits/scopes small and reviewable
- do not refactor unrelated areas
- do not invent extra features unless they clearly support the approved spec
- preserve naming consistency
- keep components modular
- separate business logic from UI rendering
- isolate financial calculations into dedicated utility/service logic
- isolate data access into clear service layers

# Code Quality Rules

Use:
- TypeScript types/interfaces for all main entities
- reusable components
- clear service abstractions for SharePoint data access
- predictable state management
- careful handling of derived/calculated values
- explicit handling of private/shared rendering differences

Avoid:
- giant monolithic components
- duplicated business logic
- hardcoded mock values left behind in production paths
- coupling UI components directly to raw SharePoint calls everywhere

# SharePoint-Specific Guidance

Prefer a practical SharePoint-native architecture that preserves the app UX.

Likely direction:
- SPFx React app
- structured SharePoint-backed entities
- document libraries for files/photos where appropriate
- controlled permissions for private vs shared view

But do not lock into a weak list-form UX just because SharePoint offers it.

# Working Style

Before major implementation steps:
- summarise the planned change
- state affected files/components/services
- identify risks or assumptions
- then implement

After implementation:
- summarise what changed
- call out any incomplete areas
- list any follow-up needed

# If There Is a Conflict

If you detect a conflict between:
- ease of implementation
- SharePoint limitations
- required UX
- required business rules

then prefer:
1. preserving the product requirement
2. proposing the best workaround
3. explicitly flagging tradeoffs

Do not silently downgrade the experience.
